    <p>It's pretty hard to go wrong here, but I would recommend 4 restaurants to get started. <i>Lupe Tortilla</i>, specifically the one off Highway 6, has great fajitas and the Steak Lupe, an enormous slab of meat and monterey jack with pico de gallo. It's a hefty but delicious meal - I've never been dissatisfied by my food at Lupe. <i>Ninfa's</i> has multiple locations, but the one on Navigation is the original and still the best. Their steak fajitas are probably the best in town, although their chicken is lacking in comparison. Also their service is exceptionally fast.</p>
    <p><i>Torchy's Tacos</i> is a chain with multiple locations focused on big fuckin' tacos with wild ingredients. They're a bit pricy ($3-$4 per) but 2-3 should be enough for most people. Highly recommend the Trashy Trailer Park and the Baja Shrimp, as well as their Queso dip. The last restaurant I'd go for is <i>Escalante's</i>. I've only eaten there a few times but the main reason I come back is for their bacon-wrapped shrimp, which can be ordered multiple ways/as part of a fajita. Honestly though they're so good I usually just eat them straight up. They're as delicious and gluttonous as they sound.</p>
    <p>Worth noting, however, that guacamole/general avocado based things are not going to be that great here in comparison to say, Southern California. After all we get most of our avocados from there, so don't expect too much. Many restaurants (Lupe included) will serve bean dip instead of Guac, in addition to salsa.</p>

    <h1>Ramen / Japanese</h1>
    <p><i>Jinya</i>: Some of the pricier ramen you can get, but definitely worth the price of admission. They have base ramens that you can pick from and add/remove ingredients as you like. Usually gets pretty busy on the weekends. </p>
    <p><i>Tiger's Den:</i> Cheaper but almost always has a wait, as the restaurant itself is tiny. I think it's just slightly below Jinya, although I like the rest of their menu (appetizer/non ramen things) better. </p>
    <p><i>Gyu-kaku Japanese BBQ:</i> This is very similar to Korean BBQ if you've ever had that; they have plates of raw meat that you cook for yourself on a grill at your table. The grilling process is super easy, and even though it's a la carte and not AYCE, Gyu-kaku is generally a pretty good value, especially if you go during lunch. Also I think their house salad is dank as fuck.</p>
    <p><i>Hokkaido Sushi:</i> Honestly Houston doesn't have particularly amazing Sushi, this one is only on here because it's cheap as shit and a great value. Aka or Sushi King are good if you want higher end fare but honestly there are better sushi spots in much of America.</p>
