    <h1>Chinese / Thai / Vietnamese</h1>
    <p><i>San Dong Noodle House:</i> My buddy's family actually runs this place. San Dong is a very affordable restaurant with delicious home-style noodles. Their whole menu is pretty good but the wonton soups are my primary recommendation.</p>
    <p><i>Spicy Hunan:</i> More of a sit-down affair, their extensive menu has everything from your standard fried rice to exotic meats like turtle and frog. Honestly this restaurant sits in the heart of Chinatown, and you could spend a few weeks trying all the different restaurants there. Just walk around the block and you'll probably find a restaurant that tickles your pickle.</p>
    <p><i>Thai Gourmet:</i> Thai food isn't quite as prominent in Houston but this spot on Richmond could give any other major city a run for their money. The atmosphere inside is actually nice enough for me to notice it, and they have a huge patio for outdoor seating. The food is slightly more expensive than other Thai offerings but it's definitely worth the upcharge.</p>
    <p><i>Pho Saigon:</i> Houston has a huge Vietnamese population and as such we get to <s>reap the rewards</s> eat boatloads of pho. Pho Saigon is probably the most well known joint in town but honestly any of the Viet restaurants in or near Chinatown are worth your time and money. You can easily get Banh Mi's for under $5 at most places. As it turns out, Pho is always delicious, even when it's 100 degrees and 80% humidity outside.</p>
