    <h1>Distinctly Houston Offerings</h1>
    <p><i>Oh My Gogi </i> and <i>YoYo's Hotdogs:</i> These 2 food trucks are probably the most well-known in Houston and kind of started the food truck craze here. Both of them can often be found in Rice Village, late at night. Gogi is Korean/Mexican fusion; their whole menu is actually surprisingly good but they are mostly known for their loaded fries. Gogi has had many imitators over the years and I've sampled a few, but the main difference is that Gogi's fries are incredibly crisp and full of flavor.</p>
    <p>YoYo's serves only one item, a bacon-wrapped dog loaded with caramelized and crispy onions, a little bit of cream cheese, and some incredible Secret Sauce (I think it might just be sriracha mayo? No idea though). It's a huge and satisfying portion, however, and can be yours for only $4. Gogi's offerings are all $5 each. 
    <p><i>Taste of Texas:</i> The Rolls-Royce of Steakhouses. When you absolutely, positively, have to have the most delicious steak on Earth...accept no substitute. I don't really know what to recommend here; it's a high-end steakhouse. Pretty much everything is good. Just bring your wallet. And don't talk to me if you order well-done. </p>
    <p><i>House of Pies:</i> This place is a "Houston classic" for some reason although I'm not exactly sure why. It's open 24/7 and the pies are pretty good (as one would expect). The food is kind of just shitty diner food though if I'm being honest. Fantastic drunchies however, this and Whataburger are probably the go-tos for drunk food.</p>
    <p><i>Sweet Paris:</i> This place serves both savory and sweet crepes for all your French cravings. I'm not sure how authentic it is (probably not at all), but really I've only had good experiences here and I think they're reasonably priced + have pretty fast service.</p>
